83rd OREGON LEGISLATIVE ASSEMBLY--2026 Regular Session
HOUSE AMENDMENTS TO
HOUSE BILL 4007
By COMMITTEE ON TRANSPORTATION
February 18
1 On page 1 of the printed bill, line 3, delete “814.487,”.
2 In line 4, delete “; and” and insert “and sections 14 and 15, chapter 1, Oregon Laws 2025 (special
3 session);”.
4 In line 5, after “814.600” insert “; and prescribing an effective date”.
5 On page 2, delete lines 23 through 27 and insert:
6 “SECTION 4. Local government and state agency regulation of the operation of powered
7 micromobility devices. Local governments, as defined in ORS 174.116, and state agencies
8 having jurisdiction over bicycle lanes, bicycle paths, sidewalks and trails of public passage
9 may:
10 “(1) Prohibit the operation of powered micromobility devices on bicycle lanes, bicycle
11 paths, sidewalks and trails; or
12 “(2) Regulate, by ordinance or rule and by traffic control device, the operation of powered
13 micromobility devices on bicycle lanes, bicycle paths, sidewalks and trails and the time, place
14 and manner of the operation of powered micromobility devices on bicycle lanes, bicycle paths,
15 sidewalks and trails.”.
16 On page 10, delete lines 17 through 39 and insert:
17 “SECTION 13. ORS 814.486 is amended to read:
18 “814.486. (1) A person commits the offense of endangering a [bicycle] vehicle operator or pas-
19 senger if:
20 “(a) The person is operating or using a [bicycle] vehicle on a highway or on premises open to
21 the public and the person carries another person on the [bicycle] vehicle who is under 16 years of
22 age and is not wearing protective headgear of a type approved under ORS 815.052; or
23 “(b) The person is the parent, legal guardian or person with legal responsibility for the safety
24 and welfare of a child under 16 years of age and the child operates, uses or rides on a [bicycle]
25 vehicle on a highway or on premises open to the public without wearing protective headgear of a
26 type approved under ORS 815.052.
27 “[(2) Exemptions from this section are as provided in ORS 814.487.]
28 “(2) This section applies to the following vehicles:
29 “(a) Bicycles;
30 “(b) Motor assisted scooters;
31 “(c) Electric personal assistive mobility devices;
32 “(d) Powered micromobility devices; or
33 “(e) Skateboards, nonmotorized scooters or in-line skates.
34 “(3) The requirement to wear protective headgear under this section does not apply if
35 wearing the headgear would violate a religious belief or practice of the person.
LC 255/HB 4007-26

1 “[(3)] (4) The offense described in this section, endangering a [bicycle] vehicle operator or pas-
2 senger, is a specific fine traffic violation. The presumptive fine for endangering a [bicycle] vehicle
3 operator or passenger is $25.
4 “(5) The first time a person is convicted of an offense described in this section the person
5 is not required to pay a fine if the person proves to the satisfaction of the court that the
6 person has protective headgear of a type approved under ORS 815.052.”.
7 On page 18, line 34, delete “26” and insert “27” and delete “27” and insert “28”.
8 In line 36, delete “27” and insert “28”.
9 On page 19, delete line 44 and insert:
10 “SECTION 29. Section 28 of this 2026 Act is repealed on January 2, 2033.
11
12 “HIGHWAY COST ALLOCATION STUDY METHODOLOGY REVIEW
13
14 “SECTION 30. Section 14, chapter 1, Oregon Laws 2025 (special session), is amended to read:
15 “Sec. 14. (1) In consultation with the study review team described in ORS 366.506, the Oregon
16 Department of Administrative Services shall undertake a review of the methodology for the highway
17 cost allocation study required under ORS 366.506.
18 “(2) The department shall examine all aspects of the methodology for the highway cost allo-
19 cation study, including but not limited to the following:
20 “(a) The revenues and expenditures included in the highway cost allocation study;
21 “(b) How costs are allocated across different classes of vehicles;
22 “(c) What constitutes a class of vehicle;
23 “(d) The data used in the highway cost allocation study;
24 “(e) The level of granularity to which cost responsibility is calculated for potential rate changes;
25 and
26 “(f) Whether equity should be analyzed based on an estimate of the future biennium’s revenue
27 and expenditures or a retrospective analysis of past actual revenue and expenditures.
28 “(3) The department may provide recommendations for updating the methodology for the study,
29 including any changes in statute needed to improve the outcome of the study and ensure fairness
30 and proportionate revenue and costs for each class of vehicle.
31 “(4) The department shall submit a report in the manner provided by ORS 192.245, and may in-
32 clude recommendations for legislation, to the Joint Committee on Transportation no later than [June
33 30, 2026] March 15, 2028.
34 “SECTION 31. Section 15, chapter 1, Oregon Laws 2025 (special session), is amended to read:
35 “Sec. 15. Section 14, chapter 1, Oregon Laws 2025 (special session), as amended by section
36 30 of this 2026 Act, [of this 2025 special session Act] is repealed on January 2, [2027] 2029.”.
